In article <1993Oct6.175526.27578@brtph560.bnr.ca>
woodstock!chris@mcnc.org writes:

> The server can verify that the client is behaving
> correctly by having the client forward everything that
> it gets as input, and the server can verify that
> given that input, the output that the server receives
> is correct.  (In essence, you're running a "correct"
> client at the server, and making sure that it produces
> the same output that the client in question is 
> producing.) 

Eh?  If you don't trust the client, how can you trust it to accurately
tell you what its input was?

In any case, if the server has to go to all the compute load of
emulating the client, there's not a lot of gain in doing that
computation at the client instead of the server...
